{"parse":{"title":"pile","pageid":50726,"redirects":[],"wikitext":"{{also|Appendix:Variations of \"pile\"}}\n==English==\n{{wp}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|en|/paɪl/}}\n* {{audio|en|en-us-pile.ogg|a=US}}\n* {{rhymes|en|aɪl|s=1}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{root|en|ine-pro|*peys-}}\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|pyle}}, from {{der|en|fro|pile}}, from {{der|en|la|pīla#pillar-pier-Latin||pillar, pier}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# A mass of things [[heap]]ed together; a [[heap]].\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1889\n|author=[[w:Henry Rider Haggard|H. Rider Haggard]]\n|title=[[w:Cleopatra (novel)|Cleopatra]]\n|volume_plain=Book II: The Fall of Harmachis\n|section=Chapter XI\n|url=http://en.wikisource.org/wiki/Cleopatra_(Haggard)/Book_II/Chapter_XI\n|isbn=1555211224\n|page=\n|passage=I climbed through, and, standing on a '''pile''' of stones, lifted and dragged Cleopatra after me.}}\n# {{lb|en|informal}} A group or list of related items up for consideration, especially in some kind of selection process.\n#: {{ux|en|When we were looking for a new housemate, we put the nice woman on the \"maybe\" '''pile''', and the annoying guy on the \"no\" '''pile'''}}\n# A [[mass]] formed in layers.\n#: {{ux|en|a '''pile''' of shot}}\n# A funeral pile; a [[pyre]].\n#* {{RQ:Dryden Metamorphoses|book=XIII|section=The Funeral of Memnon|page=463|passage=''[[w:Jupiter (mythology)|Jove]]'' with a Nod, comply'd with her Deſire; / Around the Body flam'd the Funeral Fire; / The '''Pile''' decreas'd that lately ſeem'd ſo high, / And Sheets of Smoak roll'd upward to the Sky: [...]}}\n# {{lb|en|slang}} A large amount of [[money]].\n#: {{synonyms|en|bundle|mint|q2=both informal|small fortune|q3=colloquial}}\n#: {{ux|en|He made a '''pile''' from that invention of his.}}\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1887|author=Harriet W. Daly|title=Digging, Squatting, and Pioneering Life in the Northern Territory of South Australia|page=192|passage=When they are at work they live most frugally, denying themselves every comfort and luxury till they have made a \"'''pile'''.\"}}\n# A large building, or mass of buildings.\n#* {{RQ:Scott Rob Roy|II|page=124|text=The '''pile''' is of a gloomy and massive, rather than of an elegant, style of Gothic architecture; {{...}}}}\n#* {{RQ:Dryden Aeneis|text=The '''pile''' o'erlooked the town and drew the fight.}}\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1892|author=w:Thomas Hardy|title=w:The Well-Beloved\n|passage=It was dark when the four-wheeled cab wherein he had brought Avice from the station stood at the entrance to the '''pile''' of flats of which Pierston occupied one floor{{...}}}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2021 September 22|author=Stephen Roberts|title=The writings on the wall...|journal=RAIL|issue=940|page=75|text=He [Winston Churchill] was born at Blenheim Palace, that Oxfordshire '''pile''' built for his ancestor John Churchill, 1st Duke of Marlborough, who also knew a thing or two about warfare.}}\n# A [[bundle]] of pieces of [[wrought iron]] to be worked over into bars or other shapes by rolling or hammering at a welding heat; a [[fagot]].\n# A vertical series of alternate disks of two dissimilar metals (especially copper and zinc), [[lay up|laid up]] with disks of cloth or paper [[moisten]]ed with acid water between them, for producing a current of electricity; a voltaic pile, or galvanic pile.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1893\n|author=Benjamin Park\n|title=The Voltaic Cell: Its Construction and Its Capacity\n|page=14\n|passage=The word \"'''pile'''\" is used specifically to mean the column of superposed electrodes, such as that of [[w:voltaic pile|Volta]] or [[w:zamboni pile|Zamboni]].}}\n# {{senseid|en|beam or pole driven into the ground}} {{lb|en|architecture|civil engineering}} A [[beam]], [[pole]], or [[pillar]], driven completely into the ground, usually as one of a group that constitutes a [[foundation]].\n#: {{hypo|en|friction pile|bearing pile|end bearing pile}}\n#: {{cot|en|pier<id:architectural support>|stilt#Noun}}\n# An [[atomic pile]]; an early form of [[nuclear reactor]].\n# {{lb|en|obsolete}} The [[reverse]] (or tails) of a coin.\n# A [[list]] or [[league]]\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 29, 2011\n|author=Keith Jackson\n|title=SPL: Celtic 1 Rangers 0\n|work=Daily Record\n|url=http://www.dailyrecord.co.uk/football/spl/celtic/2011/12/29/spl-celtic-1-rangers-0-86908-23665738/\n|page=\n|passage=And the moment it thumped into the net, Celtic’s march back to the top of the SPL '''pile''' also seemed unstoppable.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=20 September 2012|author=Shaun Edwards|title=Bent double and lungs burning – how Harlequins train for trophies|newspaper=The Guardian (online)|url=http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/blog/2012/sep/20/harlequins-train-trophies\n|passage=Watch Harlequins train and you get some idea of why they are back on top of the '''pile''' going into Saturday's rerun of last season's grand final against Leicester.}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* See also [[Thesaurus:lot]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|biopile|dustpile|facepile|gangpile|junkpile|leafpile|micropile|mispile|monopile|overpile|piledrive|piledriver|pileless|pilement|piler|pilewise|pilework|pileworm|pily|polypile|repile|rockpile|sandpile|shagpile|shitpile|slushpile|snowpile|stockpile|subpile|turdpile|unpile|uppile|wastepile|woodpile\n|at the top of the pile\n|atomic pile\n|Bunsen pile\n|cross and pile\n|funeral pile{{attn|en|verify?}}\n|go the whole pile\n|make a pile\n|nuclear pile|book piles|hook-and-pile fastener|puppy pile\n|pig pile|death pile\n|pile bridge\n|pile of crap\n|pile of poo\n|pile of shit| pile of cunt\n|pile shoe\n|pile driver\n|pile-driving|muscular pile\n|pile dwelling\n|rubble pile|at the bottom of the pile\n|slash pile\n|slush pile\n|three-pile\n|Zamboni pile\n|dogpile\n|helical pile\n}}\n\n=====Descendants=====\n* {{desc|haw|bor=1|paila}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top-see|mass of things heaped together; heap|heap}}\n* Arabic: {{t|ar|كَوْم|m}}\n*: Egyptian Arabic: {{t|arz|كومة|f|tr=kōma}}\n*: Moroccan Arabic: {{t|ary|عرام|tr=ʕurram}}\n* Armenian: {{t+|hy|կույտ}}, {{t+|hy|շեղջ}}, {{t+|hy|դեզ}}, {{t+|hy|զանգված}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|куп|m}}, {{t+|bg|камара|f}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|pila|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|堆|tr=duī}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|hromada|f}}, {{t+|cs|halda|f}}, {{t+|cs|kupa|f}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|stapel}}\n* Esperanto: {{t|eo|stako}}, {{t+|eo|amaso}}\n* Farefare: {{t|gur|kuko}}, {{t|gur|gilgo}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kasa}}, {{t+|fi|pino}}, {{t+|fi|läjä}}, {{t+|fi|röykkiö}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|monceau|m}}, {{t+|fr|tas|m}}, {{t+|fr|pile|f}}\n* Georgian: {{t-needed|ka}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Haufen|m}}, {{t+|de|Stoß|m}}, {{t+|de|Stapel|m}}, {{qualifier|South German, Swiss}} {{t+|de|Beige|f}}, {{t+|de|Halde|f}}\n* Greek: {{t+|el|σωρός|m}}\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|σωρός|m}}, {{t|grc|σώρευμα|n}}, {{t|grc|θίς|m}}\n* Hawaiian: {{t|haw|paila}}\n* Hebrew: {{t+|he|עֲרֵמָה}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|halom}}, {{t+|hu|rakás}}, {{t+|hu|köteg}}, {{t+|hu|nyaláb}}\n* Indonesian: {{t+|id|tumpukan}}\n* Ingrian: {{t|izh|mytty}}, {{t|izh|koko}}, {{t|izh|ropja}}, {{t|izh|runni}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|carnán|m}}, {{t|ga|cual|m|f}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|mucchio|m}}, {{t+|it|catasta|f}}, {{t+|it|pila|f}}, {{t+|it|ammasso|m}}, {{t+|it|ingorgo|m}}\n* Japanese: {{t+|ja|積み重ね|tr=つみかさね, tsumikasane}}, {{t+|ja|山|tr=やま, yama}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|무더기}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|cumulus|m}}, {{t|la|struēs|f}}\n* Lithuanian: {{t|lt|krūvà|f}}, {{t|lt|kaũpas|m}}\n* Mari:\n*: Eastern Mari: {{t|mhr|курык}}\n* Mongolian: {{t-needed|mn}}\n* Norwegian: {{t+|no|haug|m}}, {{t|no|stabel|m}}\n* Old English: {{t|ang|hēap|m}}\n* Oromo: {{t|om|tuuluu}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|کپه|tr=koppe}}, {{t+|fa|توده|tr=tude}}, {{t+|fa|کوت|tr=kut}}\n* Polish: {{t+|pl|stos|m}}, {{t+|pl|sterta|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|pilha|f}}, {{t|pt|[[monte]] ([[desordenado]])|m}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|pirwa}}, {{t|qu|qullu}}\n* Romanian: {{t+|ro|grămadă|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|ку́ча|f}}, {{t+|ru|гру́да|f}}, {{t+|ru|сто́пка|f}}\n* Sanskrit: {{t+|sa|निचय|m}}, {{t+|sa|राशि|m|f}}\n* Slovak: {{t-needed|sk}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|montón|m}}, {{t|es|rimero|m}}, {{t+|es|pila|f}}, {{t+|es|cúmulo|m}}, {{t+|es|hacina|f}}, {{t+|es|tambache|m}}, {{t+|es|ruma|f}}, {{t+|es|tauca|f}}, {{t|es|haza|f}}, {{t+|es|tonga|f}}, {{t|es|tongada|f}}, {{t+|es|rima|f}}, {{t+|es|arcina|f}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|hög|c}}\n* Turkish: {{t+|tr|pil}}, {{t+|tr|yığmak}}, {{t+|tr|yığın}}\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|ییغین|tr=yığın}}, {{t|ota|كومه|tr=küme}}\n* Ugaritic: {{t|uga|𐎖𐎎𐎕}}\n* Ukrainian: {{t+|uk|ку́па|f}}\n* Walloon: {{t+|wa|moncea|m}}, {{t+|wa|hopea|m}}, {{t+|wa|pile|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|group or list of related items}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t-needed|cmn}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|pino}}, {{t+|fi|kasa}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|pile|f}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|halom}}, {{t+|hu|csoport}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|gruppo|m}}, {{t+|it|mucchio|m}}, {{t+|it|lista|f}}, {{t+|it|elenco|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|mass formed in layers}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|пачка|f}}\n* Czech: {{t|cs|štos|m}}, {{t|cs|komínek|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kasa}}, {{t+|fi|läjä}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|pile|f}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|pila|f}}, {{t+|it|catasta|f}}\n* Turkish:\n*: Ottoman Turkish: {{t|ota|ییغین|tr=yığın}}, {{t|ota|كومه|tr=küme}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|funeral pile|pyre}}\n\n{{trans-top|''(slang in English)'' large amount of money}}\n* Hungarian: {{t|hu|[[nagy]] [[vagyon]]}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|large building, or mass of buildings}}\n* Czech: {{t|cs|honosné sídlo}}, {{t+|cs|palác|m}}\n* Hungarian: {{t|hu|[[nagy]] [[épület]]}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|ammasso|m}}, {{t+|it|blocco|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|conjunto|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|wrought iron to be worked over into bars or other shapes|fagot}}\n\n{{trans-top|vertical series of alternate disks of two dissimilar metals, laid up with disks of cloth or paper moistened with acid water between them, for producing a current of electricity; voltaic pile or galvanic pile}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|pila|f}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t-needed|cmn}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|paristo}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|pile|f}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|galvánelem}}, {{t|hu|galváncella}}, {{t|hu|galvántelep}}, {{t|hu|galvánoszlop}}, {{t|hu|Volta-oszlop}}, {{t+|hu|elem}}, {{t+|hu|telep}}, {{t+|hu|oszlop}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|pila|f}}, {{t+|it|batteria|f}}\n* Norwegian: {{t|no|batteri|n}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|pilha|f}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|гальвани́ческий элеме́нт|m}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|pila|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|architecture, civil engineering: beam, pole, or pillar, driven completely into the ground}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|pilíř|m}}, {{t+|cs|pilota|f}}\n* Hungarian: {{t+|hu|cölöp}}, {{t+|hu|karó}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|сва́я|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|atomic pile}}\n\n{{trans-see|obsolete: reverse of a coin|tails|reverse#Noun}}\n\n{{checktrans-top}}\n* German: {{qualifier|2}} {{t+check|de|Flor|m}}, {{qualifier|3}} {{t+check|de|Pfahl|m}}, {{qualifier|4}} {{t+check|de|Spitze|f}}\n* Spanish: {{qualifier|6,11}} {{t+check|es|pila|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive|often used with the preposition \"up\"}} To lay or throw into a pile or heap; to [[heap up]]; to collect into a mass; to accumulate\n#: {{ux|en|They were '''piling up''' wood on the wheelbarrow.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[cover]] with heaps; or in great abundance; to fill or [[overfill]]; to load.\n#: {{ux|en|We '''piled''' the camel with our loads.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=2013-06-22|volume=407|issue=8841|page=70|magazine=w:The Economist\n|title=[http://www.economist.com/news/finance-and-economics/21579879-buy-out-firm-really-does-focus-operational-improvements-engineers Engineers of a different kind]\n|passage=Private-equity nabobs bristle at being dubbed mere financiers. '''Piling''' debt onto companies’ balance-sheets is only a small part of what leveraged buy-outs are about, they insist. Improving the workings of the businesses they take over is just as core to their calling, if not more so. Much of their pleading is public-relations bluster.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To add something to a great number.\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=December 28, 2010|author=Owen Phillips|work=BBC\n|title=[http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/9317216.stm Sunderland 0-2 Blackpool]\n|passage=But as the second half wore on, Sunderland '''piled''' forward at every opportunity and their relentless pressure looked certain to be rewarded in the closing stages.}}\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} (of vehicles) To create a [[hold-up]].\n# {{lb|en|transitive|military}} To place (guns, muskets, etc.) together in [[three]]s so that they can stand upright, supporting each other.\n# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To form a pile or heap.\n#: {{syn|en|accumulate|pile up}}\n#: {{ux|en|Junk '''piled''' on the floor as we searched the attic for the old photograph albums.}}\n#* {{quote-journal|en|date=October 7, 2007|author=S.S. Fair|title=Vacuum Packed|work=New York Times|url=http://www.nytimes.com/2007/10/07/style/tmagazine/07samurai.html\n|passage=I darted from room to room as the see-through bagless dustbin '''piled''' high with shocking amounts of [[icky-poo]].}}\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|lay or throw into a pile}} {{l|en|heap}}, {{l|en|pile up}}; see also [[Thesaurus:pile up]]\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en|pile it high, sell it cheap|pile on|pile Pelion on Ossa|pile on the pounds|pile out|pile up|pile in}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top-see|to lay or throw into a pile|pile up}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|натрупвам}}\n* Catalan: {{t|ca|fer pila}}, {{t+|ca|amuntegar}}\n* Czech: {{t|cs|dát na hromadu}}, {{t|cs|narovnat|pf}}, {{t|cs|nakupit|pf}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kasata}}, {{t+|fi|pinota}}\n* French: {{t|fr|faire pile}}, {{t+|fr|amasser}}, {{t+|fr|empiler}}, {{t+|fr|ajouter}}\n* German: {{t+|de|stapeln}}, {{t+|de|aufstapeln}}, {{t+|de|anhäufen}}, {{t+|de|schichten}}, {{qualifier|South German, Swiss}} {{t+|de|beigen}}\n* Greek:\n*: Ancient Greek: {{t|grc|σωρεύω}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|ammucchiare}}, {{t+|it|accatastare}}, {{t|it|impilare}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|쌓다}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t+|nb|stable}}, {{t+|nb|samle}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|stable}}, {{t|nn|samle}}\n* Oromo: {{t|om|tuuluu}}\n* Portuguese: {{t|pt|fazer pilha}}, {{t|pt|fazer monte desordenado}}, {{t|pt|pôr em pilha}}, {{t+|pt|empilhar}}\n* Quechua: {{t|qu|pirway}}, {{t|qu|suk'ay}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|нава́ливать|impf}}, {{t+|ru|навали́ть|pf}}, {{t+|ru|зава́ливать|impf}}, {{t+|ru|завали́ть|pf}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|stapla}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to overload}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|натоварвам}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kasata}}, {{t+|fi|pinota}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|ammassare}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|перегружа́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|перегрузи́ть|pf}}, {{t+|ru|нагружа́ть|impf}}, {{t+|ru|нагрузи́ть|pf}} {{qualifier|to load}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to add something to a great number}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|засипвам}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kasata}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|ammassare}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|to create a hold-up}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|ruuhkauttaa}}\n* Italian: {{t|it|[[creare]] [[un]] [[ingorgo]]}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|pile}}, from {{inh|en|ang|pīl}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*pīl}}, from {{der|en|la|pīlum|t=heavy javelin}}. Cognate with {{cog|nl|pijl}}, {{cog|de|Pfeil}}. {{doublet|en|pilum}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|weapon}} {{lb|en|obsolete}} A [[dart]]; an [[arrow]].\n# The head of an [[arrow]] or [[spear]].\n# A large [[stake]], or piece of pointed [[timber]], steel etc., driven into the earth or sea-bed for the support of a building, a [[pier]], or other [[superstructure]], or to form a [[cofferdam]], etc.\n#* {{quote-book|en|year=1719\n|edition=10th\n|year_published=1864\n|author=w:Daniel Defoe\n|title=[[w:Robinson Crusoe|The Adventures of Robinson Crusoe]]\n|chapter=\n|section=Chapter VI\n|url=http://books.google.com/books?id=exRTq_qEQqAC&pg=PA68&dq=robinson+crusoe+bringing+piles&cd=2#v=onepage&q&f=false\n|page=68\n|passage=All this time I worked very hard [...] and it is scarce credible what inexpressible labour everything was done with, especially the bringing '''piles''' out of the woods and driving them into the ground; for I made them much bigger than I needed to have done.}}\n# {{lb|en|heraldiccharge}} One of the [[ordinaries]] or [[subordinaries]] having the form of a [[wedge]], usually placed [[palewise]], with the broadest end uppermost.\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en\n|pile bridge\n|pile cap\n|pile driver\n|pile dwelling\n|pile engine\n|pile plank\n|pneumatic pile\n|screw pile\n|sheet pile\n}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|obsolete: dart, arrow}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|piili}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|head of an arrow or spear}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|pää}}, {{t+|fi|nuolenpää}} {{q|arrow}}, {{t+|fi|kärki}}, {{t+|fi|keihäänkärki}} {{q|spear}}\n* Georgian: {{t+|ka|თავი}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|punta|f}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|نوک|tr=nok}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|наконе́чник|m}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|stake of pointed timber, steel etc., driven into the earth}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|кол|m}}, {{t+|bg|пилон|m}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|桩}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|kůl|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|paalu}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|pieu}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Pfahl|m}} {{q|stake}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|palo|m}}, {{t+|it|paletto|m}}\n* Kazakh: {{t+|kk|қада}}\n* Korean: {{t+|ko|말뚝}}\n* Latin: {{t|la|sublica|f}}\n* Māori: {{t|mi|tumu}}\n* Norwegian:\n*: Bokmål: {{t|nb|påle|m}}, {{t|nb|pel|m}}\n*: Nynorsk: {{t|nn|påle|m}}\n* Persian: {{t+|fa|پایه|tr=pâye}}, {{t+|fa|ستون|tr=sotun}}\n* Russian: {{t+|ru|сва́я|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-top|heraldry: one of the ordinaries}}\n* Catalan: {{t+|ca|pila|f}}\n* Czech: {{t+|cs|klín|m}}\n* Dutch: {{t+|nl|punt|n}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|kärki}}\n* French: {{t+|fr|pile|f}}\n* German: {{t+|de|Keil|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|pila|f}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|pila|f}}\n* Spanish: {{t+|es|pila|f}}\n* Swedish: {{t+|sv|kil|c}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To drive [[pile#Noun_2|pile]]s into; to fill with piles; to strengthen with piles.\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|to drive piles into}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t+|bg|забивам}}\n* Chinese:\n*: Mandarin: {{t+|cmn|打桩}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|paaluttaa}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|accatastare}}, {{t+|it|ammucchiare}}, {{t+|it|ammassare}}\n* Russian: {{t-check|ru|[[вбива́ть]] [[сва́и]]|impf}} {{attention|ru|2=was \"[[вбивать]] [[сваи]]\" - assumed sum-of-parts; if an idiom, remove the wikilinks to the individual words. see [[User:Kephir/gadgets/xte#Translation_fixing]]}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n===Etymology 3===\nApparently from {{der|en|la-lat|pilus}}. {{doublet|en|pilus}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{lb|en|usually|in the plural}} A [[hemorrhoid]].\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-see|hemorrhoid}}\n\n===Etymology 4===\nFrom {{inh|en|enm|pile}}, partly from {{der|en|xno|pil}} (a variant of {{m|fro|peil}}, {{m|fro|poil||hair}}) and partly from its source, {{der|en|la|pilus||hair}}. {{doublet|en|pilus}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun|~}}\n\n# [[hair|Hair]], especially when very [[fine]] or short; the fine [[underfur]] of certain animals. (Formerly countable, now treated as a collective singular.)\n# The raised hairs, loops or strands of a [[fabric]]; the [[nap#Etymology 2|nap]] of a cloth.\n#* {{quote-text|en|year=1785|author=w:William Cowper|title=[[s:The Task (Cowper)|The Task]]\n|passage=Velvet soft, or plush with shaggy '''pile'''.}}\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n* {{l|en|deep pile carpet}}\n* {{l|en|knotted pile}}\n* {{l|en|velvet pile}}\n\n=====Translations=====\n{{trans-top|fine or short hair}}\n* Bulgarian: {{t|bg|пух|m}}\n* Finnish: {{t+|fi|haiven}}, {{t|fi|aluskarva}}\n* Irish: {{t|ga|caitín|m}}\n* Italian: {{t+|it|peluria|f}}, {{t+|it|lanugine|f}}, {{t|it|pelucco|m}}\n* Portuguese: {{t+|pt|madeixa|f}}\n{{trans-bottom}}\n\n{{trans-see|nap of a cloth|nap}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{en-verb}}\n\n# {{lb|en|transitive}} To give a pile to; to make [[shaggy]].\n\n===Etymology 5===\nFrom {{bor|en|fr|pile||battery}}, with the pronunciation adapted to the existing English word {{m|en||pile}}. {{dbt|en|alt1=''[[#Etymology 1|Etymology 1]]''}}, which may have influenced the sense development by emphasizing the stack (“pile”) out of which early batteries were made. {{rfv-etym|en}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{en-noun}}\n\n# {{senseid|en|battery}}{{lb|en|historical|electrochemistry}} A [[battery]] {{gloss|simple device for converting chemical potential energy into usable electricity}}.\n## {{rfv-sense|en}} A battery consisting of repeated units of alternating types of metal; [[voltaic pile]].\n\n=====Derived terms=====\n{{col|en\n|thermoelectric pile|thermopile|voltaic pile\n}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|en|a=eilp|plie|IEPL|Lipe|Piel|Peil|plié|peil}}\n\n==Danish==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|da|/piːlə/|[ˈpʰiːlə]}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|da|noun form|g=c}}\n\n# {{infl of|da|pil||indef|p}}\n\n==French==\n\n===Etymology===\n{{inh+|fr|fro|-}}, from {{inh|fr|la|pīla#pillar-pier-Latin}} (through {{bor|fr|it|pila}} for the “battery” sense). The “tail of a coin” sense is probably derived from previous senses, but it's not known for sure.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{fr-IPA}}\n* {{audio|fr|Fr-Paris--pile.ogg|a=Paris}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-0x010C-pile.wav}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-LoquaxFR-pile.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Poslovitch-pile.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Vosges>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-T. Le Berre-pile.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Hérault>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Touam-pile.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Saint-Étienne>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-WikiLucas00-pile.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Lyon>>)}}\n* {{audio|fr|LL-Q150 (fra)-Jérémy-Günther-Heinz Jähnick-pile.wav|a=<<France>> (<<Somain>>)}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{fr-noun|f}}\n\n# [[heap]], [[stack]]\n#: {{uxi|fr|'''pile''' de cartons|'''stack''' of cardboard boxes}}\n# [[pillar]]\n# [[battery]]\n#: {{uxi|fr|'''pile''' électrique|electric '''battery'''}}\n# [[tails]]\n#: {{uxi|fr|'''pile''' ou face|heads or '''tails'''}}\n# {{lb|fr|heraldiccharge}} {{l|en|pile}}\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|fr|pile ou face}}\n\n====Descendants====\n* {{desc|bor=y|en|pile}}\n* {{desc|bor=y|ht|anpil}}\n* {{desc|bor=y|km|ពិល|tr=pɨl}}\n* {{desc|bor=y|mg|pila}}\n* {{desc|bor=y|rad|pil}}\n* {{desc|bor=y|tr|pil|t=battery}}\n* {{desc|bor=y|vi|pin}}\n\n===Adverb===\n{{fr-adv}}\n\n# {{lb|fr|colloquial}} [[just]], [[exactly]]\n# {{lb|fr|colloquial}} [[dead]] (of stopping etc.); [[on the dot]], [[sharp]] (of time), [[smack]]\n\n====Derived terms====\n* {{l|fr|pile-poil}}\n\n===Further reading===\n* {{R:fr:TLFi}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{l|fr|plie}}, {{l|fr|plié}}\n\n==Friulian==\n\n===Etymology 1===\nFrom {{inh|fur|la|pīla||mortar}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{fur-noun|f|pl=pilis}}\n\n# [[basin]]\n# [[mortar]] (vessel used to grind things)\n\n=====Synonyms=====\n* {{sense|basin}} {{l|fur|vâs}}\n* {{sense|mortar}} {{l|fur|mortâr}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\nFrom {{inh|fur|la|pīla||pillar}}.\n\n====Noun====\n{{fur-noun|f|pl=pilis}}\n\n# [[pile]] (architecture)\n\n==Italian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{it-pr|pìle}}\n\n===Etymology 1===\n[[pseudo-anglicism|Pseudo-anglicism]], from {{bor|it|en|pile}} (textile).\n\n====Noun====\n{{it-noun|m|#}}\n\n# [[polar fleece]], [[fleece]]\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{nonlemma}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{head|it|noun form|g=f}}\n\n# {{plural of|it|pila}}\n\n===Anagrams===\n* {{anagrams|it|a=eilp|peli|plié}}\n\n==Ladino==\n\n===Alternative forms===\n* {{l|lad|pila}}\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|lad|[ˈpi.læ]|[ˈpi.lɛ]|[ˈpi.le]}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{lad-noun|g=f|pl=piles}}\n\n# ''Aki Yerushalayim and French orthography spelling of '''''{{l|lad|pila}}''''' used in [[Kosovo]], [[North Macedonia]], [[Old Yishuv]] of [[Jerusalem]], West [[Bulgaria]] and [[Ruse]].''\n\n{{cln|lad|nouns in Aki Yerushalayim orthography|nouns in French orthography}}\n\n==Latin==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|la|noun form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|la|pilus||voc|s}}\n\n==Latvian==\n\n===Noun===\n{{lv-noun|f|5th}}\n\n# [[drip]]\n#: {{ux|lv|Es pievienoju vaniļas ekstrakta '''pili''' savam karstajam kakao.|t=I put a '''drip''' of vanilla extract in my hot cocoa.}}\n# [[dribble]] {{gloss|a small amount of a liquid}}\n# [[drop]]\n#: {{ux|lv|Maisījumam pievienot trīs eļļas '''piles'''.|t=Put three '''drops''' of oil into the mixture.}}\n\n====Declension====\n{{lv-decl-noun|pi|e|5th||l|ļ|extrawidth=-60}}\n\n==Lower Sorbian==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|dsb|/ˈpʲilɛ/|[ˈpʲilə]}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|dsb|noun form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|dsb|piła||dat//loc|s|;|nom//acc|d}}\n\n==Middle English==\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|enm|noun|altform=1}} \n\n# {{alt form|enm|pilwe}}\n\n==Old English==\n\n===Noun===\n{{ang-noun|m}}\n\n# {{alternative form of|ang|pyle}}\n\n==Polish==\n\n===Pronunciation===\n{{pl-pr|hh=pilę}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|pl|noun form|g=f}}\n\n# {{inflection of|pl|piła||dat//loc|s}}\n\n==Portuguese==\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|pt|verb form}}\n\n# {{pt-verb form of|pilar}}\n\n==Serbo-Croatian==\n\n===Etymology 1===\n{{inh+|sh|sla-pro|*pilę|t=chick}}.<ref>{{R:sh:ERHJ|pȉle|123|2}}</ref>\n\n====Pronunciation====\n* {{sh-IPA|pȉle}}\n* {{hyphenation|sh|pi|le}}\n\n====Noun====\n{{sh-noun|pȉle|n|dim=pilénce}}\n\n# [[chick]]\n\n=====Declension=====\n{{sh-decl-noun\n|pile|pilići\n|pileta|pilića\n|piletu|pilićima\n|pile|piliće\n|pile|pilići\n|piletu|pilićima\n|piletom|pilićima\n}}\n\n=====Related terms=====\n* {{l|sh|pȉlād}}\n* {{l|sh|pìletina}}\n\n====See also====\n* {{l|sh|kokoš}}\n* {{l|sh|pijevac}} / {{l|sh|pevac}}\n* {{l|sh|pileći gulaš}}\n\n====References====\n<references/>\n\n====Further reading====\n* {{R:sh:HJP|eV5hWhc%3D}}\n\n===Etymology 2===\n{{nonlemma}}\n\n====Verb====\n{{sh-verb form}}\n\n# {{inflection of|sh|piliti||3|p|pres}}\n\n{{C|sh|Baby animals|Birds}}\n\n==Spanish==\n\n===Verb===\n{{head|es|verb form}}\n\n# {{es-verb form of|pilar}}\n\n==Yola==\n\n===Etymology===\nFrom {{inh|yol|enm|pyle}}, from {{der|yol|fro|pile}}, from {{der|yol|la|pīla}}.\n\n===Pronunciation===\n* {{IPA|yol|/piːl/}}\n\n===Noun===\n{{head|yol|noun}}\n\n# {{l|en|pile}}\n#* {{quote-book|yol|year=1867|chapter=A YOLA ZONG|number=9|page=88|title=SONGS, ETC. IN THE DIALECT OF FORTH AND BARGY|passage=A clugercheen gother: all, ing '''pile''' an in heep,|translation=A crowd gathered up: all, in '''pile''' and in heap,}}\n\n===References===\n* {{R:Poole 1867|page=88}}"}}